[2]
Date: Sat 11 Mar 2006
From: Pablo Nart <pablo.nart@terra.es>
Source: Yahoo news, Wed 8 Mar 2006 [edited]
<http://news.yahoo.com/s/afp/20060308/hl_afp/malaysiahhealthdisease_06030817261
5>

Malaysia declared that an outbreak of hand-foot-and-mouth disease in
the eastern state of Sarawak has escalated into an epidemic, with
some 200 cases being reported daily.
Health Minister Chua Soi Lek said the disease had reached epidemic
proportions "because of the increase in the number of cases in the
beginning of this year [2006]."
State health officials have recorded a total of 3087 cases since 1
Jan 2006. The disease is spread by poor hygiene and causes fever,
rashes and painful blisters in the mouth and on the hands and feet.
All kindergartens in the state have been shut down to prevent the
spread of the disease, and hospitals are on alert to treat and
isolate people, Chua said.
"All the hospitals, especially in towns like Miri and Kuching and
Sibu, where it's the worst, the hospitals have to be ready for
isolations. We usually put them in isolation wards because it spreads
very fast," he told AFP.
Chua said authorities were on the lookout for outbreaks in the rest
of Malaysia, where it is endemic, and a public awareness campaign
would soon be launched.
"We have to go on a big information drive to make the people more
aware of the problem," said Chua, who sharply criticized
kindergartens that continue to remain open in Sarawak.
"The mentality is that if the school is not affected, then why should
they close down," he said, dismissing the offenders as
"profit-oriented."
Sarawak suffered outbreaks of hand-foot-and-mouth disease in 1997,
2000 and 2003 in what officials say is a 3-year cycle. The 1997
outbreak killed 31 people.
Chua said the government was investigating why the disease was
rearing its head so regularly.
